tion":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Parr in Lancashire, or from residence at an enclosure (Middle English <i>parr</i>, Old English <i>pearr</i>).","German: from Middle Low German <i>parre</i> ‘parish, district, minister's house’; a metonymic occupational name for a parson or for someone who worked in a parsonage or manse. Compare   Pfarr  .","English: variant of   Pear   with the common late Middle English and early modern English change of <i>-er</i>- to <i>-ar-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pare","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Henri, Laurent, Normand, Fernand, Alphonse, Clermont, Elphege, Alain, Benoit, Gaston, Girard.","French (<b>Paré</b>): occupational name for someone who finished cloth, from the past participle of <i>parer</i> ‘to prepare’.","English: variant of   Parr  ."]},{"name":"Parman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Parmann</b>: variant of   Parr  .","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Bärmann</b> (see   Barmann  ).","English: variant of   Pearman  ."]},{"name":"Porr","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ulrike, Gunther.","German:","metonymic occupational name for a grower or seller of leeks or other vegetables, from Middle High German <i>porre</i>, <i>pforre</i> ‘leek’ (from Latin <i>porrum</i>)."]},{"name":"Pfarr","meanings":["South German: from Middle High German <i>pfarr</i> ‘district, parish’ or <i>pfarre(r)</i> ‘parish priest’, hence an occupational name for a parson, or a topographic name for someone who lived near the parsonage."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Parr was born about 1500, in Dorking, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Perley, was 21 and his mother, Josephine Roper, was 21. He married Mary Waller in 1520, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters."},"et":{"Abt 1500–":"umbes 1500–Surnud","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1500–1592":"1500–1592","1520–1563":"1520–1563","1520–1588":"1520–1588","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1523–Male":"1523–Surnud","1529–1573":"1529–1573","1539–1580":"1539–1580","1520–1584":"1520–1584","1529–1580":"1529–1580","1480–1530":"1480–1530","1480–1550":"1480–1550","1550":"1550","Abt 1500":"umbes 1500","1592":"1592","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","1523":"1523","1500":"1500","1588":"1588","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","8 March 1539":"8. märts 1539","1584":"1584","1573":"1573","1529":"1529","1539":"1539","Dorking, Surrey, England":"Dorking, Surrey, England","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wales":"Wales","England":"England","Dorking, Mole Valley district, Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Dorking, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1500–":"noin 1500–Kuollut","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1500–1592":"1500–1592","1520–1563":"1520–1563","1520–1588":"1520–1588","1520–Female":"1520–Kuollut","1523–Male":"1523–Kuollut","1529–1573":"1529–1573","1539–1580":"1539–1580","1520–1584":"1520–1584","1529–1580":"1529–1580","1480–1530":"1480–1530","1480–1550":"1480–1550","1550":"1550","Abt 1500":"noin 1500","1592":"1592","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","1523":"1523","1500":"1500","1588":"1588","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","8 Mar